1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,931
The syntactical world is governed by a deductive calculus,

2
00:00:04,031 --> 00:00:07,475
which we can picture as a theorem-proving computer.

3
00:00:07,600 --> 00:00:10,011
Feed it a set of axioms as input, and it

4
00:00:10,111 --> 00:00:14,030
will output their logical consequences — which we call theorems.

5
00:00:14,133 --> 00:00:17,391
The symbols of this system divide into logical and

6
00:00:17,491 --> 00:00:20,616
non-logical, and the axioms divide the same way.

7
00:00:20,733 --> 00:00:24,729
The logical axioms are like the operating system running in the

8
00:00:24,829 --> 00:00:29,541
background of all mathematics, determining how the logical symbols behave.

9
00:00:29,666 --> 00:00:33,554
Different choices of logical axioms may give different logics —

10
00:00:33,654 --> 00:00:37,415
in this series we will work with classical first-order logic,

11
00:00:37,515 --> 00:00:41,086
and I will dedicate a later video to non-classical logics.

12
00:00:41,133 --> 00:00:44,472
On top of this logical foundation, different fields of

13
00:00:44,572 --> 00:00:49,186
mathematics introduce their own constants, functions, and relations, along

14
00:00:49,286 --> 00:00:52,753
with their own axioms, giving rise to different theories

15
00:00:52,853 --> 00:00:56,001
like number theory, field theory, and group theory.

16
00:00:56,133 --> 00:01:00,627
Formally, a theory is the set of all consequences of its axioms

17
00:01:00,727 --> 00:01:06,168
— i.e. everything the theorem-proving computer can output from those inputs.

18
00:01:06,266 --> 00:01:09,783
So, on the syntactic side, mathematic truth

19
00:01:09,883 --> 00:01:13,062
means provability in a formal calculus.

20
00:01:13,133 --> 00:01:17,161
On the semantic side, truth is given by Tarski's definition: a

21
00:01:17,261 --> 00:01:20,423
sentence is true if and only if it holds in every

22
00:01:20,523 --> 00:01:24,085
model. Let us make this precise — it may feel technical

23
00:01:24,185 --> 00:01:27,348
for a moment, but it leads somewhere interesting.

24
00:01:27,466 --> 00:01:31,317
Formally, a structure — which we denote with the symbol M —

25
00:01:31,417 --> 00:01:35,671
is given by a tuple consisting of a domain, or universe, together

26
00:01:35,771 --> 00:01:41,028
with interpretations of the constants, functions, and relations in the language.

27
00:01:41,200 --> 00:01:44,914
To define the natural numbers with addition and multiplication, for

28
00:01:45,014 --> 00:01:47,932
instance, we need at least the symbols zero, one, the

29
00:01:48,032 --> 00:01:52,202
addition function, the multiplication function, and the less-than relation.

30
00:01:52,333 --> 00:01:55,550
We interpret zero and one as expected.

31
00:01:55,600 --> 00:01:58,524
Functions act like computer programs: they take

32
00:01:58,624 --> 00:02:01,612
inputs and produce a uniquely determined output.

33
00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:06,347
Relations are slightly more abstract — formally, the less-than

34
00:02:06,447 --> 00:02:09,566
relation is interpreted as the set of all pairs

35
00:02:09,666 --> 00:02:11,895
(a, b) such that a is less than b.

36
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,200
Note that functions are just special relations where

37
00:02:15,300 --> 00:02:18,247
the output is uniquely determined by the inputs.

38
00:02:18,333 --> 00:02:21,983
So the successor function would map to the set of all pair

39
00:02:22,083 --> 00:02:25,991
of numbers such that the second is one greater than the first.

40
00:02:27,066 --> 00:02:31,076
And the addition function is formally the set of all triples

41
00:02:31,176 --> 00:02:33,680
(a, b, c) such that a plus b equals c.

42
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:38,419
To evaluate a simple equation like one plus two

43
00:02:38,519 --> 00:02:41,081
equals three, we map the constants as expected

44
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:43,525
and then check whether the resulting

45
00:02:43,625 --> 00:02:46,220
triple belongs to the addition relation.

